'''Tzibte Yux''', '''Tzib Te Yux''', or '''Tzib'te Yux''', is a [[Preceramic Period in Belize|Preceramic]] [[rock shelter]] and archaeological site in the [[Rio Blanco National Park]], [[Toledo District|Toledo]], [[Belize]]. It is thought to have been occupied by [[Palaeoindian]] settlers during 10500 BC{{snd}}6500 BC.
== Description == Tzibte Yux is a rockshelter measuring some {{convert|121|ft|m|abbr=on}} long and {{convert|14.8|ft|m|abbr=on}} wide at its widest point.{{sfn|Prufer|Meredith|Alsgaard|Dennehy|2017|p=322}} Its entrance, protected by a silicified limestone and conglomerate overhang, sits some {{convert|26|ft|m|abbr=on|sigfig=1}} above Blue Creek during the [[dry season]], though this decreases to less than {{convert|6|ft|m|abbr=on|sigfig=1}} during the [[wet season]].{{sfn|Prufer|Meredith|Alsgaard|Dennehy|2017|p=322}} Its floor is relatively flat and composed of sediments, predominantly [[Pachychilus|jute snail]] shells deposited by former pre-Columbian inhabitants.{{sfn|Prufer|Meredith|Alsgaard|Dennehy|2017|p=323}}
Fishtail- and Lowe-style stemmed [[biface|bifacial points]] have been recovered from Tzibte Yux, the former dated 10450 cal BC{{snd}}10085 cal BC, the latter 8275 cal BC{{snd}}6650 cal BC.{{sfn|Braswell|2022|p=90|loc=fig. 4.5}}{{sfn|Stemp|Awe|Marcus|Helmke|2021|p=419}} Human remains have also been recovered from the rock shelter.{{sfn|Prufer|Meredith|Alsgaard|Dennehy|2017|p=323}}
== Study == Tzibte Yux was discovered by the Uxbenka Archaeological Project in 2009.{{sfn|Prufer|Meredith|Alsgaard|Dennehy|2017|p=321}} Subsequently, nine blocks or units, ie Units 1{{en dash}}9, covering some {{convert|194|ft2|m2|abbr=on|sigfig=2}} of the rock shelter's floor, were excavated to a mean depth of some 2.5 ft (0.75 m) during 2012{{en dash}}2015.{{sfn|Prufer|Meredith|Alsgaard|Dennehy|2017|pp=321-323}} A piece of charcoal found at the bottom of a red clay layer in Unit 1, some 23 in (58 cm) below the floor's surface, was dated to 10571 cal BC{{snd}}10526 cal BC. Most material in other units produced dates within 10500 cal BC{{snd}}6500 cal BC, though Unit 7 yielded a later date of 890 cal AD{{snd}}975 cal AD at 18.5 in (47 cm) below surface.{{sfn|Prufer|Meredith|Alsgaard|Dennehy|2017|pp=323-325}}
